The mechanical behavior of wound dressings is important to be determined because these materials must exhibit specific physical properties such as sustainability and flexibility during storage and use [44]. The mechanical characteristics of the CS/SF and CS/SF/N-CQDs/α-TCP mats, both before and after cross-linking, were estimated, and the elastic modulus, tensile strength, and elongation at break were measured as the most critical factors for mechanical properties evaluation. Fig. 7
                         shows the stress-strain curves of the nanofibrous scaffolds. With the addition of N-CQD/α-TCP NPs to chitosan/silk fibroin nanofibers, the elastic modulus increased from 51.13 ± 3.4 MPa to 95.33 ± 4.1 MPa. Also, tensile strength and elongation at break were changed from 0.71 ± 0.2 to 1.16 ± 0.6 and 2.05 ± 0.1 to 3.2 ± 0.2, respectively. The mechanical performance of both as-spun scaffolds was improved by chemical treatment. In the case of the CS/SF/N-CQD/α-TCP mats, Young's modulus and tensile strength were found to be 99.99 ± 2.7 MPa and 1.7 ± 0.8, respectively. In contrast, elongation at break decreased from 3.2 ± 0.2 % to 2.69 ± 0.2 % (Table 1
                        ). The ultimate tensile strength (UTS) and tensile modulus of human skin are normally in the range of 1–40 MPa and 15–150 MPa, respectively [45,46]. Clearly, the tensile modulus and ultimate tensile strength of the cross-linked CS/SF and CS/SF/N-CQD/α-TCP scaffolds lie within the normal range of human skin.
